y Modern period that coincided with the establishment of which images of the body were to be considered ‘decent’ and representable, and which disapproved, censored, or prohibited. Simultaneously, artists and the public became increasingly interested in the depiction of specific body parts or excretions. This book explores the concept of indecency and its relation to the human body across drawings, prints, paintings, sculptures, and texts. The ten essays investigate questions raised by such objects about practices and social norms regarding the body, and they look at the particular function of those artworks within this discourse. The heterogeneous media, genres, and historical contexts north and south of the Alps studied by the authors demonstrate how the alleged indecency clashed with artistic intentions and challenges traditional paradigms of the historiography of Early Modern visual culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aArt, European. 0aHuman beings in art. 0aObscenity (Aesthetics). 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aDecorum, Body History, Sex, Ugliness, Beauty.1 aCuneo, Pia F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Mambro Santos, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmerson, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonietz, Fabian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonietz, Fabian, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKirch, Miriam Hall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMeurer, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichter, Mandy, econtributor.4ctb4https://